body:
I am new to the Verilator and trying to create a minimal C++ model driver for me and my students. While browsing the examples I noticed the following clean up routines:

https://github.com/verilator/verilator/blob/7bfc1a00a723cd91d8d52c146b5e7b45844a2ed6/examples/make_hello_c/sim_main.cpp#L34-L41

https://github.com/verilator/verilator/blob/7bfc1a00a723cd91d8d52c146b5e7b45844a2ed6/examples/make_tracing_c/sim_main.cpp#L112-L124

From https://github.com/verilator/verilator/blob/master/docs/guide/example_cc.rst:

```
....
delete top;
delete contextp;
return 0;
```

I was pondering
- `delete top`
- `delete contextp`
- `return 0`.

In my experiments I saw that `delete top` was required to successfully write the FST trace file (otherwise Gtkwave could not open it). `delete contextp` did not have any effect. Regarding `return 0` I found [this reference](https://stackoverflow.com/a/204483) from which I understand that `return 0` can be omitted.

- What is the purpose of these statements?
- If they should not be omitted, why?

<details><summary>If needed here is my testbench driver</summary>
<pre><code>
#include "Vmajority_of_five_tb.h"
#include "verilated.h"
int main(int argc, char** argv, char** env) {
        VerilatedContext* contextp = new VerilatedContext;
        
        contextp->traceEverOn(true);
        // Compute traced signals
        
        contextp->commandArgs(argc, argv);
        Vmajority_of_five_tb* top = new Vmajority_of_five_tb{contextp};
        top->clk = 0;
        while (!contextp->gotFinish()) {
	        contextp->timeInc(1);
	        top->clk = !top->clk;
	        top->eval();
        }
        top->final();
        delete top;
        // Must be deleted manually. Otherwise the signal trace is not written properly.
}
</code></pre>
</details>
